      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-de",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the hemolysis index QoI must be ≤ 5% on the production mesh relative to the finest mesh studied, computed using the Richardson extrapolation procedure per ASME V&V 20."
      },
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (coarse 2.1 M cells, medium 5.8 M cells, fine 14.2 M cells) was conducted at the worst-case operating point (6 L/min, 3500 RPM). GCI for the normalised hemolysis index was 3.2% (medium→fine), within the 5% acceptance threshold. The production mesh is the medium mesh, balancing accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-tc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-tc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, haematocrit) must be documented with measurement uncertainty; boundary conditions in the CFD model must be set to the reported experimental nominal values with uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo."
      },
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental conditions are fully documented in Stewart et al. (2012) with ±2% flow rate uncertainty and ±0.5% speed uncertainty. CFD boundary conditions were set to nominal experimental values; Monte Carlo sampling over the reported uncertainty ranges was performed across 500 realisations, confirming that boundary condition uncertainty contributes less than 8% to total hemolysis index variance."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-oc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-oc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria",
        "description": "The normalised hemolysis index predicted by CFD must agree with experimental measurements within ±20% at all 5 operating points, accounting for combined simulation and experimental uncertainty at the 95% confidence level."
      },
      "rationale": "At all 5 operating points the CFD-predicted normalised hemolysis index fell within ±14% of the experimental mean, well inside the ±20% acceptance band. The 95% confidence intervals derived from Monte Carlo UQ overlap with experimental uncertainty bounds at every point. Systematic over-prediction bias of +6% is consistent with the power-law hemolysis model's known conservatism."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-rqoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-rqoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "The validation QoI (normalised hemolysis index) must be the same quantity used in the regulatory submission and must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint (plasma free haemoglobin rise). The mapping between the computational scalar and the clinical measure must be documented."
      },
      "rationale": "The normalised hemolysis index (NHI) computed by the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model is the same scalar reported in the regulatory 510(k) submission and is directly proportional to plasma free haemoglobin rise per ISO 10993-4. The mapping is documented in the model description report (MDR-COU2-v3, §4.2). No surrogate QoI substitution was made."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-rvac",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-rvac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation experiments must be conducted on the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, the same blood analogue fluid, and within the same operating envelope (flow 2–8 L/min, speed 2500–4500 RPM) as the COU. Extrapolation beyond the validated envelope is not permitted without additional justification."
      },
      "rationale": "All validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry (STEP file SHA-256 verified against production CAD), the same 36% glycerol-water blood analogue, and spanned the 2–8 L/min / 2500–4500 RPM COU envelope. No extrapolation beyond the validated operating range is required for the regulatory submission. Validation-to-COU relevance is rated high."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-nse",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-nse",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical solver error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to five orders of magnitude reduction in residuals for all transport equations. Round-off error must be assessed and shown to be negligible relative to discretization error."
      },
      "rationale": "All production simulations achieved six-orders-of-magnitude residual reduction for continuity, momentum, and hemolysis scalar equations. Double-precision arithmetic was used throughout; round-off error estimated via interval arithmetic is three orders of magnitude below the GCI-estimated discretization error, confirming negligibility."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-ue",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-ue",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "A documented independent review of simulation setup files, boundary condition assignments, and post-processing scripts must be completed by a reviewer not involved in the original simulation. Any discrepancies identified must be resolved and documented."
      },
      "rationale": "An independent senior CFD engineer (not part of the original simulation team) reviewed all OpenFOAM case dictionaries, boundary condition files, and Python post-processing scripts. Three minor discrepancies in probe placement were identified and corrected; the corrected results were re-run and showed less than 0.3% change in NHI, confirming robustness of the original findings."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-mf",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-mf",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria",
        "description": "The choice of turbulence model and hemolysis constitutive law must be justified relative to the flow regime (Re, rotating machinery) and validated against at least one independent dataset beyond the primary FDA benchmark. Sensitivity of NHI to turbulence model choice must be quantified."
      },
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on published benchmark comparisons for rotating machinery (Hariharan et al. 2011) and confirmed by a model-form sensitivity study comparing k-ε RNG, SST k-ω, and LES on the medium mesh at 6 L/min. SST k-ω produced the lowest model-form uncertainty (±9% NHI spread vs ±22% for k-ε RNG). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was validated against a second independent dataset (Bludszuweit 1995 Couette viscometer data), achieving ±12% agreement."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-mi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-mi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs acceptance criteria",
        "description": "All material properties (blood analogue viscosity, density), geometric parameters (impeller clearance, volute dimensions), and operating parameters (flow rate, rotational speed) must be sourced from traceable measurements with documented uncertainty. Sensitivity of NHI to each uncertain input must be ranked via Sobol indices."
      },
      "rationale": "Fluid properties were measured in-house at 37°C using a cone-and-plate rheometer (±1.5% viscosity uncertainty). Geometric dimensions were extracted from the FDA-released STEP file with tolerances per the published drawing. Sobol first-order sensitivity indices from the 500-sample Monte Carlo study identified impeller tip clearance (S1=0.31) and inlet flow rate (S1=0.27) as the dominant input uncertainties, together explaining 58% of NHI variance. These inputs were prioritised for tighter characterisation in the production campaign."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-ts",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/morrison-cou2-ts",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Experimental hemolysis measurements must be available from at least 3 independent test samples (pump units) at each operating point to characterise inter-unit variability, or a documented justification provided for why fewer samples are acceptable."
      },
      "rationale": "The FDA benchmark dataset includes measurements from 3 independent pump units fabricated to the same STEP geometry at each of the 5 operating points. Inter-unit coefficient of variation for NHI ranged from 4.2% to 7.8%, confirming acceptable manufacturing repeatability. The CFD model targets the ensemble mean, and the inter-unit spread is fully captured within the experimental uncertainty bounds used in the output comparison."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou2-eip",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor addresses scenarios where a validation study uses a surrogate fluid, scaled geometry, or analogue device whose input parameters must be shown equivalent (via non-dimensional mapping or similarity analysis) to the clinical COU. In this assessment, the validation experiments are conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry (STEP file SHA-256 verified) using the same 36% glycerol-water blood analogue specified in the COU protocol, operated within the identical flow-rate and rotational-speed envelope. No geometric scaling, fluid substitution beyond the protocol-specified analogue, or device-class bridging is involved. Because the experimental and COU configurations share the same geometry, the same fluid, and the same operating conditions by design, there is no non-trivial equivalency mapping to establish or verify. Applying this factor would require constructing a similarity argument between two configurations that are definitionally identical, rendering the assessment vacuous. The factor is therefore not applicable to COU2 and is excluded from the credibility score computation. This determination was reviewed and concurred by the lead V&V engineer and the regulatory affairs representative on 2026-03-14."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-accepted-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-lead-vv-engineer",
    "role": "Lead V&V Engineer",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All twelve assessed credibility factors achieved levels meeting or exceeding their required levels at Model Risk Level 5. The one not-applicable factor (Equivalency of input parameters) was reviewed and confirmed inapplicable because the validation and COU configurations are geometrically and operationally identical by protocol design. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification across 500 realisations confirmed that combined simulation and experimental uncertainty is within the ±20% acceptance band at all 5 operating points. Model form sensitivity analysis demonstrated SST k-ω is the appropriate turbulence model for this rotating-machinery hemolysis regime. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through validated CFD results to the regulatory claim is complete and traceable. On the basis of this structured evidence the credibility assessment team unanimously accepts the CFD hemolysis prediction model for use in the Class III VAD regulatory submission.",
